===============================
SPRING IoC & DEPENDENCY MANAGEMENT NOTES
===============================

The IoC (Inversion of Control) container in Spring is used for TWO main operations:

1) Spring Bean Life Cycle Management
2) Dependency Management

--------------------------------
DEPENDENCY MANAGEMENT
--------------------------------

Dependency Management means:
Arranging dependent Java class objects for a target Java class object
so that interaction between them can happen.

Target Class:
- The Java class that USES services of another class.

Dependent Class:
- The Java class whose services are USED by the target class.

--------------------------------
EXAMPLES
--------------------------------

Target Class        Dependent Class
------------        ----------------
Flipkart            DTDC
Student             CourseMaterial
Cricketer           CricketBall

Meaning:
- Flipkart uses DTDC courier services
- Student uses CourseMaterial for preparation
- Cricketer uses CricketBall for playing

--------------------------------
WAYS TO IMPLEMENT DEPENDENCY MANAGEMENT
--------------------------------

Dependency Management can be implemented in TWO ways:

1) Dependency Lookup (DL)
2) Dependency Injection (DI)

================================
1) DEPENDENCY LOOKUP (DL)
================================

Definition:
Dependency Lookup means the TARGET class itself searches and gets
the dependent class object from different resources.

Important Point:
- Logic to get dependent object is written inside the target class.
- Target class PULLS the dependent object.

--------------------------------
REAL LIFE EXAMPLES
--------------------------------

Example 1:
Student (target) requests CourseMaterial (dependent)
from institute manually.

Example 2:
Java Application (target) gets required object (dependent)
from JNDI registry by searching it.

--------------------------------
JNDI (Java Naming and Directory Interface)
--------------------------------

JNDI is used to:
- Store objects
- Search objects
- Retrieve objects using a name (nickname)

Example JNDI Registries:
- RMI Registry
- COS Registry
- Tomcat Registry
- WebLogic Registry

--------------------------------
JNDI OPERATIONS
--------------------------------

bind     -> Add object reference to registry
rebind   -> Replace existing object reference
unbind   -> Remove object reference
lookup   -> Search and get object reference

--------------------------------
KEY NOTES
--------------------------------

- Object created inside method -> Local scope
- Object created inside class (non-static) -> Object scope
- Object created as static -> Class scope

To make an object GLOBAL and ACCESSIBLE:
- Place its reference inside JNDI registry

--------------------------------
JDBC vs JNDI
--------------------------------

JDBC:
Java App ---> JDBC API ---> Database
Used for CRUD operations

JNDI:
Java App ---> JNDI API ---> JNDI Registry
Used for lookup operations

--------------------------------
PROBLEM WITH DEPENDENCY LOOKUP
--------------------------------

- Target class is tightly coupled with dependent class
- Programmer has extra burden to write lookup logic
- Not flexible

================================
2) DEPENDENCY INJECTION (DI)
================================

Definition:
Dependency Injection means the SERVER / CONTAINER / FRAMEWORK
creates and injects dependent objects into the target object
AUTOMATICALLY at runtime.

Important Point:
- Target class does NOT create or search dependent object
- Container PUSHES the dependency

--------------------------------
EXAMPLES
--------------------------------

Example 1:
Student object is created â†’ CourseMaterial is injected automatically.

Example 2:
Servlet Container injects ServletConfig into Servlet.

--------------------------------
ADVANTAGES OF DEPENDENCY INJECTION
--------------------------------

- Loose coupling
- Less programmer burden
- Easy maintenance
- Easy testing

--------------------------------
DISADVANTAGES OF DEPENDENCY INJECTION
--------------------------------

- Wrong configuration may inject unwanted objects
- Requires correct configuration

================================
SPRING FRAMEWORK & DEPENDENCY MANAGEMENT
================================

Spring Framework supports:
- Dependency Lookup (DL)
- Dependency Injection (DI)

But in REAL-TIME PROJECTS:
ðŸ‘‰ Dependency Injection is preferred over Dependency Lookup

--------------------------------
SPRING DEPENDENCY INJECTION TYPES
--------------------------------

Spring supports DI in 7 ways:

BASIC INJECTIONS:
1) Setter Injection
2) Constructor Injection
3) Field Injection (Best)

ADVANCED INJECTIONS:
4) Aware Injection
5) Interface Injection
6) Lookup Method Injection
7) Method Replacer Injection

--------------------------------
XML BASED CONFIGURATION
--------------------------------

In XML configuration, Spring mainly supports:

- Setter Injection
- Constructor Injection

XML Tags:
<property>        -> Setter Injection
<constructor-arg> -> Constructor Injection

--------------------------------
FINAL EXAM POINT
--------------------------------

In most real-time scenarios,
Dependency Injection is preferred over Dependency Lookup
because it provides loose coupling and better maintainability.

